bug.short_desc: openvswitch python3 tests fails due to PEP 538 warning
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1281092 build.log
openvswitch tests fails on Python 3.6.0 on Fedora 26 and rawhide, but the same tests works on Python 3.5.0 on Fedora 25 and on "upstream" Python 3.6.0.
After some analysis I found that "testsuite" (part of autoconf) and autoconf itself enforces LC_ALL=C and testsuite, by default, also checks that stderr should be equal of what you specify (or empty).
But with https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Changes/python3_c.utf-8_locale stderr includes "Python runtime initialized with LC_CTYPE=C (a locale with default ASCII encoding), which may cause Unicode compatibility problems. Using C.UTF-8, C.utf8, or UTF-8 (if available) as alternative Unicode-compatible locales is recommended." and this cause the tests to fail
In attachment you may find a fail generated with fedpkg scratch-build
Actually I workarounded the problem on openvswitch spec file by setting "PYTHONCOERCECLOCALE=0", but you'll have the problem if you compile openvswitch by yourself

Hi!
This is a new intended behaviour of Python which is done in coordination with upstream (PEP 538 should land in Python 3.7), therefore some tools will have to be adjusted to account for it.
I'm reassigning this bug to the openvswitch component.

After looking at some of the code, indeed the problem is that the test suite is checking for specific stderr output, however PEP 538 adds additional output to stderr making the test cases to fail.
A similar issue manifested at autoconf [0] as well due to this change.
For openvswitch the test suite should be changed preferably with coordination with upstream, as when PEP 538 lands in Python 3.7 the same test failures will be observed by then.
For the time being, working around the issue with [1] should be enough, I'd leave the bug open though to track the issue.
[0] https://github.com/peti/autoconf-archive/pull/117/files [1] http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/cgit/rpms/openvswitch.git/commit/?id=7d75ee018a115bb45bc3a32b43df02b2abb39e00
Timothy did you have any communication with upstream regarding the issues?

Yes, they approved my commit with the following comment:
It's amazing that the Python maintainers think it's a good idea to randomly break everyone's stuff in this way. Just imagine what would happen if glibc one day started printing a warning like this on stderr if users had a locale they didn't approve of.
See https://mail.openvswitch.org/pipermail/ovs-dev/2017-June/333542.html
